f determining who was an indio and who was not-especially since it was an all-encompassing construct connoting subservience and political personhood and at times could refer to people from Mexico, Peru, or South or East Asia. Van Deusen demonstrates that the categories of free and slave were often not easily defined, and she forces a rethinking of the meaning of indio in ways that emphasize the need to situate colonial Spanish American indigenous subjects in a global context.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIndiansxCivil rights. 0aIndiansxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistoryy16th century. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzLatin America. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzSpain. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822375692zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822375692423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822375692.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles